summary:
The Security Council,

Recalling its previous resolutions on Lebanon, including 425 (1978), 426 (1978), 501 (1982), 508 (1982), 509 (1982), 520 (1982), and 1310 (2000), 
Recalling the Secretary-General's conclusion that Israel had withdrawn its forces from Lebanon in accordance with resolution 425 (1978), 
Emphasizing the interim nature of UNIFIL,

Welcomes the report of the Secretary-General on UNIFIL and endorses his observations and recommendations; 
Extends the mandate of UNIFIL for six months, until 31 July 2001; 
Decides to return UNIFIL's military personnel to the operational level by 31 July; 
Reiterates its support for Lebanon's territorial integrity, sovereignty, and political independence; 
Calls on the Government of Lebanon to ensure its effective authority in the south and to increase the deployment of its armed forces; 
Welcomes the establishment of checkpoints by Lebanon and encourages a calm environment in the south; 
Calls on parties to respect the withdrawal line and to cooperate with UNIFIL; 
Condemns acts of violence and urges parties to respect UNIFIL personnel's safety; 
Commends UNIFIL for fulfilling its mandate and supports its continued efforts; 
Welcomes UNIFIL's contribution to demining and encourages further assistance; 
Requests the Secretary-General to continue consultations and report to the Security Council; 
Looks forward to the early fulfilment of UNIFIL's mandate; 
Endorses the general approach for UNIFIL's reconfiguration and requests a detailed report by 30 April 2001; 
Decides to review the situation by early May 2001; 
Stresses the importance of a comprehensive, just, and lasting peace in the Middle East.
